# Security and Telegram Rules

## Security Rules

- Never hard-code bot tokens, API keys, private paths, personal Chat IDs, or credentials.
- Store secrets under `REMOTE_CODER_HOME` (default `~/.remote-coder`). Per-project metadata and allowlists live in `projects.json`. Bot tokens and webhook secrets are stored in the **OS keyring** (service `remote-coder`, account `<project>:bot_token` / `<project>:webhook_secret`) when a keyring backend is available; the persisted file records `secret_backend: keyring` and holds no secret material. On first run with a keyring, legacy plaintext secrets are migrated once (`migrate_plaintext_to_keyring`, with a `.pre-keyring.bak` backup). When no keyring backend is available, the server falls back to plaintext in `projects.json` only for an existing legacy file or with `REMOTE_CODER_ALLOW_PLAINTEXT_SECRETS=1`, and otherwise fails closed at startup. Persistence goes through the `SecretStore` abstraction (`app/projects/secret_store.py`); route any new secret through it, keep tokens out of `to_public_dict`, logs, and errors, and restrict `projects.json` to owner-only permissions.
- Validate Telegram Chat ID/User ID allowlists before processing commands or natural-language job requests. Allowlists are per registered project / bot instance.
- Never run Git or AI work outside registered project paths.
- Never execute user messages directly as shell commands.
- Avoid `shell=True`; use list-based subprocess arguments.
- Dangerous options such as `--dangerously-skip-permissions` must be documented and used only after project path and user allowlist checks.
- Commit AI-generated changes only to a separate branch. Do not add automatic deployment to the MVP.
- Declarative mode addons (`~/.remote-coder/addons/*.yaml`) are read-only only: `read_only` must be boolean `true`, write/commit/push capability stays builtin-exclusive, and `prompt` text never grants permission. Parse with `yaml.safe_load`, reject builtin/trigger collisions, and skip a bad file per-file with a short reason token only (no paths/tokens/field values in logs). Rationale: `docs/mode-addons-design.md`.
- Admin UI logs must not store full Telegram message text. Log only a first-line preview of at most 80 characters.
- Do not place bot tokens or project absolute paths in log message bodies.
- Pass `chat_id`, `job_id`, `project`, and similar context through structured `logging extra` fields that match `LOG_RECORD_CONTEXT_KEYS`.

## Telegram Rules

- Process only allowed Chat ID/User ID values.
- Reject unauthorized requests quietly or with a minimal response.
- Send short, clear messages for received, started, completed, and failed states.
- Natural-language job requests must show the current project, target branch, and model, then wait for an inline Yes/No button response before creating a job. Text `y`/`Y` confirmation is not supported.
- Completion messages must include project name, branch name, commit hash, changed files, model information when available, token usage when available, and an error summary on failure.
- Successful AGENT/AGENT_FIX completion messages expose an `Open PR` button only when the Job has both a branch and a commit; command execution must still revalidate Job ownership and remote state.
- Failure messages should summarize the root cause and point to the log location instead of sending long logs.
- Keep command help available through `/help`; `/help` and `/help <topic>` must remain text-only and must not attach functional inline buttons.
- Commands with selectable options (`/model`, `/status`, `/branch`, `/rebase`, `/stop`, `/pr`, `/clear`, `/monitor`) should show inline buttons when called without arguments.
- `/pr` choices and direct arguments are scoped to succeeded Jobs from the current bot project and Telegram chat; do not expose or accept branches owned by another project or chat.
- Inline button callback data must reuse the existing slash-command execution path after callback authentication.
- `/init` resets the chat's default model override and pending confirmation state. It must not alter SQLite conversation memory or Git repositories.
- There is no `/project` command: the Telegram bot is bound to one registered project; webhook URL uses the first **16 hex characters** of the SHA-256 digest of the bot token as the path segment (not the raw token, not the full digest).
